Introduction to ggplot

Load relevant packages:

pacman::p_load(tidyverse,lubridate,ggthemes,tidyquant,readr,readxl)

# load data:
Time_series <- read_csv("Time_series.csv")

Anatomy of a ggplot object

GGplot is a grammar of graphics designed for composing graphics by combining independent components.

Step 1: Format Data

Lets do some quick formatting before plotting our data.

# Some data wrangling, for plot prep:

# Filter the Time_series data frame to only include 2022, and reassign
# it to the same data frame:

Time_series %>% 
  filter(year(DATE) == 2022) -> Time_series

Step 2: Plot

Line Plot

Another type of plot is the line plot, it is great for time series data, or data that has a temporal element:

Time_series %>%
  filter(year(DATE) == 2022) %>% 
# Canvas
  ggplot(aes(x = DATE, y = TOTAL_POINTS)) +
  # Geometries
  geom_line(size = 1, color="midnightblue") + # Adds a line
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) + # Adds a smoothed line
  # Formatting
  expand_limits(y = 0) + # Adds 0 to the
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::number_format(scale = 1 / 1e6, suffix = "M")) +
  labs(
    title = "Point Redemptions 2022",
    subtitle = "Trend line indicates downward trend heading into peak season",
    x = "",
    y = "Points",
    caption = "Source: NDWHS_PROD.NDWHS_PL.BURN_FACT"
  ) -> g # Assign to an object

Inspect the ggplot element:

# View(g)

Types of Plots

The Scatter Plot

The scatter plot is good for exploring the relationship between continuous variables. More advanced versions of this plot include the lollipop chart. Lets look at the relation between Nectar points and value:

# Data Manipulation:
points_dist <- Redemptions_and_Total_Points %>%
    
    select(REDEMPTIONS, TOTAL_POINTS) %>%
    
    group_by(REDEMPTIONS) %>%
    summarize(TOTAL_POINTS= sum(TOTAL_POINTS)) %>%
    ungroup()

# Scatter Plot
points_dist %>%
    
    ggplot(aes(x = REDEMPTIONS, y = TOTAL_POINTS)) +
    
    geom_point(alpha = 0.5, size = 2)+
    scale_y_continuous(label=scales::comma_format())

Bar/Column Plot

Bar charts are another great type of chart, particularly for summarizing categorical data.

# Some data manipulation first:

Redemptions_by_segment <- Segment_Redemptions %>%
  
  select(REWARD_SEGMENT,REDEMPTIONS) %>%
  
  group_by(REWARD_SEGMENT) %>%
  summarize(total_redemptions = sum(REDEMPTIONS)) %>%
  ungroup()

# Plot the bar:

Redemptions_by_segment %>%
  filter(REWARD_SEGMENT != is.na(REWARD_SEGMENT)) %>% 
  mutate(REWARD_SEGMENT = REWARD_SEGMENT %>% as_factor() %>% fct_reorder(total_redemptions)) %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(REWARD_SEGMENT, total_redemptions)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels= scales::comma_format(), expand = c(0.005,0.005))+
  geom_col(fill = "#2c3e50") +
  coord_flip()

Histogram/Density plots

Another useful type of chart is a histogram or density plot, they are useful for inspecting the distribution of a specific variable:

Sample_data %>%
  ggplot(aes(TRAN_SPEND)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 20) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 140), breaks = seq(0, 140, by = 20)) +
  #facet_wrap( ~ NECTAR_SEGMENT) + # if we want to do it to all segments.+
  theme_bw()
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_bar).

In the same family we can consider the box-plot, which is useful for comparing distributions across groups:

# Box Plot
Segment_Redemptions %>%
  filter(REWARD_SEGMENT != is.na(REWARD_SEGMENT)) %>% 
    
    ggplot(aes(fct_reorder(REWARD_SEGMENT, REDEMPTIONS), REDEMPTIONS)) +
    
    geom_boxplot() +
    coord_flip() +
    theme_tq()+
    xlab("")+
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma_format())

Formatting

Formatting involves tweaking and perfecting aspects of the visualization as you see fit. Formatting the colors of a ggplot object:

Redemptions_by_segment %>%
  filter(REWARD_SEGMENT != is.na(REWARD_SEGMENT)) %>% 
  mutate(REWARD_SEGMENT = REWARD_SEGMENT %>% as_factor() %>% fct_reorder(total_redemptions)) %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(REWARD_SEGMENT, total_redemptions)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels= scales::comma_format(), expand = c(0.005,0.005))+ # Examples of Formatting
  geom_col(fill = viridisLite::viridis(n = 20)[10])+ # Examples of Formatting
  coord_flip() # Examples of Formatting

R also provides some functionality to convert color schemes from RGB to HEX and vice versa.

# To RGB
col2rgb("slateblue")
##       [,1]
## red    106
## green   90
## blue   205
col2rgb("#2C3E50")
##       [,1]
## red     44
## green   62
## blue    80
# To HEX
rgb(44, 62, 80, maxColorValue = 255)
## [1] "#2C3E50"

This will be useful when customizing and themeing plots.

Exercises

Something similar to the others in terms of exercises. Important to start with something basic, layers of difficulty as we go on, already been done before and tweak. If bar chart, but use this metric instead for example. Progressively more difficult. 3 exercises. Find a new geom/layer and come up with a new perspective of an existing, tidyverse geom documentation.

Formatting the plot part 1

Format the y-axis such that the numbers are not in scientific notation. Hint: you will need to add the following function to you plot: scale_y_continuous() and pass a specific value to the label that will be the following scales::comma_format(). You will need the scales package for this to work!

Segment_Redemptions %>% 
 ggplot()+ # Carry on the second argument from part 1.1 
  + # Geom_layer
  # scale_y_continuous_layer

If you are struggling with the above try the following link for inspiration: https://scales.r-lib.org/

Formatting the plot part 2

Lets continue formatting the plot by adding and formatting the plot title and axis titles. This can be done by adding the labs() function to the plot layers.

# Carry on the layers from the previous 2 exercises and add:
+ labs()

run ?labs() in the console to get an idea for the arguments that need to be passed to the function to change the labels.

Finish off the plot by layering a theme onto your plot, call the theme() family of functions and pick one that you like.
